 3, 4) \\quad \\text{(nonnegative solutions)} \\\\\n                    & = (-1, -2, -3, -4) \\quad \\text{(negative solutions)}\n\\end{split}\n\\]\n\nWe need to compute the number of such ordered quadruples where the product \\( abcd = 12 \\).\n\nAssume \\( a, b, c, d \\ge 0 \\) (Since \\( a^4 + b^4 + c^4 + d^4 > 0 \\Rightarrow abcd > 0 \\)). We divide into cases based on the number of negative values:\n\n1. Case 0: No negative values. All positive.\n2. Case 1: One negative value (e.g., \\(-x, y, z, w\\)).\n3. Case 2: Two negative values (e.g., \\(-x, -y, z, w\\)).\n4. Case 3: Three negative values (e.g., \\(-x, -y, -z, w\\)).\n5. Case 4: All negative.\n\nWe need to count solutions for each case and sum them up.\n\nCase 0:\nWe check for \\( (1, 2, 3, 4) \\) directly:\n\\[ 1^4 + 2^4 + 3^4 + 4^4 = 1 + 16 + 81 + 256 = 354 \\neq 48 \\]\n\nCase 1:\nAssume one negative, e.g., \\(a\\) is negative, others \\(b, c, d\\) positive:\n\\[ a^4 - b^4 - c^4 - d^4 = 48 \\]\nSince \\(a, b, c, d\\) are symmetric in the above equation, it suffices to calculate one quadruple and consider permutations:\nAssume \\( (a=1, b=2, c=3, d=4) \\):\n\\[ 1^4 - 2^4 - 3^4 - 4^4 = 1 - 16 - 81 - 256 = -352 \\neq 48 \\]\n\nCase 2:\nAssume \\(a, b\\) negative, \\(c, d\\) positive (or symmetric permutation):\nThis case results in smaller absolute values and cannot satisfy \\( a^4 + b^4 + c^4 + d^4 = 48 \\).\n\nCase 3:\nAssume all \\( a, b, c, d \\) negative:\n\\[ a^4 + b^4 + c^4 + d^4 = 48 \\]\nThis requires exploration but leads to higher values.\n\nCase 4:\nNo solutions, since \\(abcd = -12\\) is not possible with all terms positive.\n\nThus, no solutions through to generalization. We need to check boundaries explicitly, but this problem seems complex without a clear set of boundary solutions, indicating a deeper inquiry or complex polynomial behavior needs to be explored further.\n\nThus, the exact number of solutions or the structure of solution space (via symmetric constraints, etc.).", "truth": "8